{{Infobox person | name = Fred Batt | imagesize = | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1955|9|2|df=y}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | other_names = | known_for = Demonologist on [[Most Haunted]] | occupation = | spouse = | children = | website = https://www.twitter.com/demonologist666 }}
'''Fred Batt''' (born 2 September 1955) is a former businessman, nightclub owner, singer, actor and self-styled [[Demonology|demonologist]] and historian known for his regular appearances on the British [[Paranormal television|paranormal]] [[reality television]] series ''[[Most Haunted]]''. He claims to be the United Kingdom's only demonologist.<ref name=Dorking/>
Batt states that his interest in the occult began as a teenager. He made his first appearance as a presenter on ''[[Most Haunted]]'' in 2008 on a live Hallowe'en special;<ref name=Dorking>[http://www.dorkingandleatherheadadvertiser.co.uk/Dorking-Demonologist-Fred-Batt-new-series-Haunted/story-22723798-detail/story.html 'Dorking Demonologist Fred Batt to front new series of Most Haunted' - ''Dorking and Leatherhead Advertiser'' - 19 August 2014]</ref> he had previously appeared as a guest on the show in 2003 at his nightclub Caesar's in Streatham. He became a regular presenter on the show in the 2010-11 series and rejoined for the current series in 2013.
From 1994 to 2010 he owned Caesar's, a 1,900-capacity nightclub on Streatham High Street;<ref>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/fred-batt-17146a1a Batt's profile on [[LinkedIn]]]</ref> in an episode of ''[[Most Haunted]]'' filmed here in 2003 he claimed the venue was haunted by the spirit of [[Ruth Ellis]] who had worked there.<ref>[http://www.streathamguardian.co.uk/news/4075421.Ghostbusters_to_inspect_doomed_nightclub/ 'Ghostbusters to inspect doomed Caesar's nightclub' - ''Streatham Guardian'' - 26 January 2009]</ref> In 2004 Batt became involved in lengthy licensing hearings lasting 13 hours in Lambeth when the police and local councillors objected to Caesar's receiving a new alcohol licence because of the heavy drain the venue placed on police resources.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2004/jun/30/localgovernment.comment 'The Longest Lambeth Licensing Hearing in Living Memory' - ''[[The Guardian]]'' - 30 June 2004]</ref> In 2009 he became the first person in the UK to be fitted with a light adjustable lens (LAL) to correct vision impairment.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8392749.stm 'Giving old eyes a new lease of life' - [[BBC News]] - 5 December 2009]</ref>
Fred Batt has lived in [[Dorking]] in [[Surrey]] since 1984.<ref name=Dorking/>
