'''Li Kuge''' ({{zh|c=李窟哥}}) was one's people of old [[Khitan people]] in Tang Dynasty period.

==History==
During the Tang Dynasty period, Li Kuge (李窟哥) was just one people is old Khitan people at Tang Dynasty, he get surname Li (李) from Tang Government because distinguish oneself at a battle about Babarian in East Manchuria. [[Li Jinzhong]] was grand child of Li Kuge.

==Family==
*[[Li Jinzhong]], grand son of Li Kuge 
*[[Li Kaigu]], adopted son of [[Li Jinzhong]]
*[[Sun Wanrong]], one's wife's brother of [[Li Jinzhong]]

[[Category:Khitan history]]

This is a '''list of German far-right periodicals (post-1945)'''. In post-[[World War II]] Germany, after the defeat of the [[Nazis]] and [[Nazi Germany]], the far-right was outlawed by the Allied occupation forces, preventing political continuity of the [[Nazi Party]] in a new, post-war form. In [[West Germany]], reformed far-right parties were able to reestablish a foot hold in the [[Bundestag|national parliament]] in the early years of the new Federal Republic, courtesy in part to the post-war issues the new country faced. With the recovery of the German economy, the ''[[Wirtschaftswunder]]'', the far-right declined in appeal. The far-right, from the 1960s, was characterised by fragmentation and infighting. Following the [[German reunification]], in the early 1990s, the far-right has regained strength and become more of a threat to the democratic Germany again.<ref>{{cite web |first=Richard |last=Stöss|date=12 September 2006|title=Geschichte des Rechtsextremismus|trans-title=History of the far-right|url=http://www.bpb.de/politik/extremismus/rechtsextremismus/41907/geschichte-des-rechtsextremismus|language=German |work=[[Federal Agency for Civic Education]]|location= |access-date=1 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Hoser |date=|title=Rechtsextremismus|trans-title=The Far-right|url=https://www.historisches-lexikon-bayerns.de/Lexikon/Rechtsextremismus#Rechtsextremismus_und_Herrschaft_des_Nationalsozialismus|language=German |work=[[Historisches Lexikon Bayerns]]|location= |access-date=1 December 2018 }}</ref>
In [[East Germany]], a communist country, the far-right was declared extinct by the government despite the fact that a quarter of all members of the ruling communist party, in 1954, had formerly been members of the Nazi Party. Despite the official line, racism and far-right ideology existed and, towards the end of the country's existence in the late 1980s, increased. It was however swept under the carpet by the ruling authorities as ordinary violence and hooliganism rather than being allowed to be seen as a resurface of far-right ideology.<ref>{{cite web |first=Bernd |last=Wagner|date=2 January 2018|title=Vertuschte Gefahr: Die Stasi & Neonazis|trans-title=Hidden danger: The Stasi and Neo-Nazis|url=https://www.bpb.de/geschichte/deutsche-geschichte/stasi/218421/neonazis|language=German |work=[[Federal Agency for Civic Education]]|location= |access-date=1 December 2018 }}</ref>
The German [[Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution]] classifies the [[Far-right politics|far-right]] ({{lang-de|Rechtsextremismus}}) as a movement against the equality of all people as guaranteed by the German constitution, and as enemies of the democratic nature of the German state. Their aim is to establish an authoritarian state, modelled on the ''[[Führerprinzip]]''. The far-right places undue value on race and ethnicity which results in xenophobia and racism. [[Antisemitism]] is a core principal of their ideology.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rechtsextremismus|trans-title=The Far-right|url=https://www.verfassungsschutz.de/de/service/glossar/_lR#rechtsextremismus|language=German |work=[[Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution]]|location= |access-date=30 November 2018 }}</ref> Far-right publications generally glorify Germany's Nazi past and the armed forces of the era, the [[Wehrmacht]] and [[Waffen-SS]], offering historically revisionist publications and attempting to promote the myth of the ''[[Clean Wehrmacht]]'' and ''Clean Waffen-SS''. Far-right publisher are however careful to not out-rightly [[Holocaust denial|deny or trivialise]] [[the Holocaust]], this being a criminal offence in Germany, as many have been prosecuted for such offences in the past.<ref name="Geschichte" />
The German Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution, as of 2017, classifies three political parties as far-right, the [[National Democratic Party of Germany]] (NPD), ''[[Die Rechte]]'' and [[Der III. Weg]], with a combined membership of 6,050.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rechtsextremistische Parteien|trans-title=Far-right Parties|url=https://www.verfassungsschutz.de/de/arbeitsfelder/af-rechtsextremismus/zahlen-und-fakten-rechtsextremismus/rechtsextremistische-parteien-2017s|language=German |work=[[Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution]]|location= |access-date=30 November 2018 }}</ref>
Historically, a small number of long-standing far-right newspapers and magazines have been published since the early 1950s, like the ''[[National Zeitung]]'' and ''[[Nation Europa]]'', while a larger number of publications have only existed for a short duration.<ref name="Bdp" >{{cite web |first=Gabriele|last=Nandlinger|date=25 May 2007|title=Rechtsextreme Schwarz-Weiß-Malerei - Ein kurzer Überblick über die tonangebenden rechtsextremen Printmedien|trans-title=Far-right black & white vision: A short overview of the major far-right print medias|url=http://www.bpb.de/politik/extremismus/rechtsextremismus/41714/rechtsextreme-schwarz-weiss-malerei?p=all|language=German |work=[[Federal Agency for Civic Education]]|location= |access-date=30 November 2018 }}</ref> The pulp magazine ''[[Der Landser]]'', which existed for almost 60 years, glorified the German armed forces and omit the war crimes committed by Wehrmacht and Waffen-SS, without providing any historical context and was eventually terminated after a complaint by the [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]].<ref name=cardw>{{cite news|author=Carla Bleiker|title=Publishing house terminates German pulp mag 'Der Landser'|url=http://www.dw.de/publishing-house-terminates-german-pulp-mag-der-landser/a-16989362|accessdate=14 April 2015|work=Deutsche Welle|date=3 December 2018}}</ref>
The far-right print media in Germany is predominately organised in the ''{{ill|Gesellschaft für freie Publizistik|de}}'', GfP, the largest far-right association of publishers, authors and book sellers, which was formed by former SS officers and Nazi officials in 1960.<ref name="Rand" /> The number of far-right publishers in Germany independent of political parties has declined from 45 in 2001 to 30 in 2016.<ref name="Geschichte" >{{cite web |first=Thomas|last=Pfeiffer|date=19 December 2016|title=Das Kapillarsystem – Geschichte und Entwicklung der rechtsextremistischen Presse|trans-title=History and development of the far-right press|url=http://www.bpb.de/politik/extremismus/rechtsextremismus/239223/geschichte-der-rechtsextremen-presse|language=German |work=[[Federal Agency for Civic Education]]|location= |access-date=1 December 2018 }}</ref>
==Newspapers & magazines== Major far-right newspapers and magazines:<ref name="Rand" >{{cite web |first=Anton|last=Maegerle|date=23 December 2016|title=Was liest der rechte Rand? Der Blätterwald|trans-title=What does the right edge read? Publications|url=http://www.bpb.de/politik/extremismus/rechtsextremismus/239620/der-rechte-rand-publikationen|language=German |work=[[Federal Agency for Civic Education]]|location= |access-date=30 November 2018 }}</ref> {| class="wikitable sortable" |- align="center" style="background:#dfdfdf" ! width="150" scope=col| '''Name''' ! width="50" scope=col| '''Location''' ! width="50" scope=col| '''{{Tooltip|Est|Established}}''' ! width="50" scope=col| '''{{Tooltip|Dis|Disestablished}}''' ! width="70" scope=col| '''Circulation''' ! width="50" scope=col| '''Published''' ! width="100" scope=col| '''Publisher''' ! width="200" scope=col| '''Notes''' ! scope=col class=unsortable| '''Ref''' |- align="left" |{{ill|Der Freiwillige|de}} |[[Reinsfeld]] |1956 |2014 |5,000 (2006) |Two monthly |{{ill|Munin Verlag|de}} |Central organ of the [[HIAG]], a veterans organisation of the [[Waffen-SS]], classified as revisionist and idolising the Waffen-SS{{-}}Merged into ''DMZ Zeitgeschichte'' in 2014, which is published by {{ill|Dietmar Munier|de}} |<ref name="Taz" >{{cite news |first=Andreas|last=Speit|date=27 March 2014|title=Neues von der Waffen-SS|trans-title=New stuff from the Waffen-SS|url=http://www.taz.de/!373751/|language=German |work=[[Die Tageszeitung]]|location=[[Berlin]] |access-date=30 November 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Der Freiwillige|trans-title=|url=https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&cqlMode=true&query=idn%3D011814322 |language=German |work=[[German National Library]]|location= |access-date=30 November 2018 }}</ref> |- align="left" |[[Deutsche Geschichte]] |[[Gilching]] |1990 |Active |10,000 (2016) |Two monthly |Verlagsgesellschaft Berg mbH |Produced by one of the largest independent far-right publishers in Germany, the periodical contains historical revisionist articles on military history |<ref name="Rand" /> |- align="left" |[[Deutsche Militärzeitschrift Zeitgeschichte]] |[[Selent]] |2012 |Active | |Two monthly |Verlagsgruppe Lesen & Schenken |An offshoot of the ''{{ill|Deutsche Militärzeitschrift|de}}'', which caters for a more moderate readership, the ''Deutsche Militärzeitschrift Zeitgeschichte'' caters for the far-right, glorifying the [[Waffen-SS]]{{-}}The publication absorbed the Waffen-SS vetrans publication ''{{ill|Der Freiwillige|de}}'' in 2014 |<ref name="Rand" /> |- align="left" |{{ill|Deutsche Stimme|de}} |[[Riesa]] |1976 |Active |21,000 (2007) |Monthly |Deutsche-Stimme-Verlag |Official party organ of the far-right [[National Democratic Party of Germany]], classified as xenophobic, nationalistic and Antisemitic |<ref name="Bdp" /> |- align="left" |[[National Zeitung]] |[[Munich]] |1951 |Active |38,000 (2007) |Weekly |DSZ Druckschriften- und Zeitungs-Verlag GmbH |Originally published as ''Deutsche Soldaten-Zeitung'', renamed ''Deutsche National-Zeitung und Soldaten-Zeitung'' in 1961 and ''Deutsche National-Zeitung'' in 1963. Merged in 1999 with ''Deutscher Anzeiger'' to become ''National Zeitung''.{{-}} The [[Bavarian Office for the Protection of the Constitution]] classifies the ''National Zeitung'' as propagating a xenophobic, nationalist and revisionist world view{{-}}Functioned as the semi-official party organ of the [[German People's Union]], the DVU, with both controlled by [[Gerhard Frey (politician)|Gerhard Frey]] |<ref name="Bdp" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Rechtsextremismus: Verlage und Versandhandel|trans-title=The Far-right: Publishers and mail order businesses|url=http://www.verfassungsschutz.bayern.de/rechtsextremismus/definition/erscheinungsformen/verlage/index.html|language=German |work=[[Bavarian Office for the Protection of the Constitution]]|location= |access-date=17 November 2018 }}</ref> |- align="left" |[[Nation Europa]] |[[Coburg]] |1951 |200