{{Infobox person | name = Vasily Modestov | image = Brockhaus and Efron Encyclopedic Dictionary B82 43-4.jpg | imagesize = | caption = | birthname = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1839|1|24}} | birth_place = [[Novgorod Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1907|2|13|1839|1|24}} | death_place = [[Rome]], [[Italy]] | occupation = historian, philologist, publicist and translator | years_active = | spouse = | website = | awards = }}
'''Vasily Ivanovich Modestov''' ({{lang-ru|Василий Иванович Модестов}}, 24 January 1839, [[Valdaysky District|Valday]], [[Novgorod Governorate]], [[Imperial Russia]], — 13 February 1907, [[Rome]], [[Italy]]) was a Russian [[historian]], [[philologist]], [[publicist]] and [[translator]].
A [[Saint Petersburg University]] graduate who lectured at the [[Odessa University|Odessa]], [[Kazan University|Kazan]] and [[Kiev University|Kiev Universities]], as well as his [[alma mater]] (in 1886—1889), Modestov was a prominent authority on the history and culture of [[Ancient Rome]], as well as earlier [[Apennine Peninsula]] cultures ([[Etruscan civilization]], [[Messapii]]). He contributed to ''[[Istorichesky Vestnik]]'', ''[[Golos (newspaper)|Golos]]'', ''Nov'', ''Filologicheskoye Obozrenye'', as well as the [[Brockhaus and Efron Encyclopedic Dictionary]], providing entries on the history and culture of Rome. Modestov translated into Russian semimal works by [[Tacitus]] (The Complete Tacitus, Vols. 1—2, 1886—87), [[Horace]], [[Spinoza]], as well as the ''[[:de:Reallexikon des classischen Alterthums für Gymnasien|Reallexikon des classischen Alterthums für Gymnasien]]''. Among his best-known original works were ''The History of Ancient Rome'' (Vols. I-II, 1902—1909) and ''Tacitus and his Work. Historical and Literary Study'' (Тацит и его сочинения. Историко-литературное исследование, 1864).<ref>[http://dic.academic.ru/dic.nsf/bse/109981/%D0%9C%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%B5%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%B2 Василий Иванович Модестов]. The Great Soviet Encyclopedia // Большая советская энциклопедия. — М.: Советская энциклопедия. 1969—1978.</ref><ref>[http://centant.spbu.ru/spbant/db/mod.html Василий Иванович Модестов]. Biography at the Saint Petersburg Antiquity Scholars site</ref>
